com.vector.cfg.model.access

Interface IDefRefWildcard

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    EDefRefWildcard

    @PublishedApi(value=CHANGES_FORBIDDEN)
public interface IDefRefWildcard

    DefRef Wildcards

    The DefRef class supports so called wildcards, which could be used to match on multiple packages at once, like the /[MICROSAR] wildcard matches on any DefRef package starting with /MICROSAR. E.g. /MICROSAR, /MICROSAR/S12x, ....

    Every wildcard is of type IDefRefWildcard. An IDefRefWildcard instance could be passed to the DefRef.create(IDefRefWildcard, String) method to create a DefRef with wildcard information.

    Custom DefRef Wildcards

    You could create your own wildcard by implementing the interface IDefRefWildcard. Please choose a good name for your wildcard, because this could be displayed to the user, e.g. in Validation results. The matches(DefRef) method shall return true, if the passed DefRef matches the wildcard constraints.

    Every wildcard string shall have the notation /[NameOfWildcard].
    E.g. /[MICROSAR], /[!MICROSAR]    .

    • Method Detail

      • continueRefinementSearchFor

        @PublishedMethod
boolean continueRefinementSearchFor(DefRef moduleDefRef)
        Returns true, if the refinement search shall continue for this definition of this IDefRefWildcard. If the method returns false, the refinement search algorithm will stop at this definition.

        This could be used to filter e.g. all /MICROSAR definition which also refine from /AUTOSAR, but /AUTOSAR shall be included in the Wildcard.

        Parameters:
        moduleDefRefs - The found refinement modules
        Returns:
        true, if the refinement search shall continue with this definition

      • getWildcardString

        @PublishedMethod
java.lang.String getWildcardString()
        Gets the user friendly wildcard string.

        Every wildcard string shall have the notation /[NameOfWildcard]. E.g. /[MICROSAR], /[!MICROSAR].

        Returns:
        the wildcard string

      • matches

        @PublishedMethod
boolean matches(DefRef defRefToMatch)
        Returns true in the wildcard matches the DefRef.

        Attention:You must not evaluate the DefRefStringWithoutPackagePart of the DefRef! The second part of the DefRef could be different (see isParentOf check!).

        Parameters:
        defRefToMatch - the DefRef to match
        Returns:
        true, if the wildcard matches the defRef
